        "body": "The chapter opens with David doing what kings do — numbering the people, appointing commanders, deploying troops in thirds (vv. 1-2). The tactical arrangement of three columns under Joab, Abishai, and Ittai the Gittite reflects sound ancient Near Eastern military practice; dividing forces prevented encirclement and allowed for strategic flexibility in forested terrain. But the opening verses immediately surface the chapter's first tension: David wants to fight alongside his men (v. 2), and his men refuse him. Their argument is not flattery — it is strategic theology. 'You are worth ten thousand of us' (v. 3). The king's person is the kingdom's irreplaceable asset; if half the army dies and David lives, the campaign can continue; if David dies, even a victory is catastrophic. David accepts their reasoning and takes his post beside the gate (v. 4).\n\nThe deployment is competent and the counsel is sound, but the chapter's dramatic engine is ignited by verse 5. David's battle order — the only one recorded — has nothing to do with tactics and everything to do with his son. 'Deal gently for my sake with the young man Absalom.' The word *na'ar* (young man) is the term of tenderness, not the term of political or military reality. The narrator ensures the reader cannot miss the public nature of this command: 'all the people heard when the king charged all the commanders concerning Absalom' (v. 5). Every soldier in the army knew the king's will before a single sword was drawn.\n\nThis verse is the chapter's interpretive key. Whatever follows — Joab's defiance, the unnamed soldier's refusal, the messenger's evasion — is measured against this openly stated command. David's love for Absalom is not private sentiment; it is a royal order that enters the chain of command. The tension the narrator is building is not simply between father and son but between the king's personal will and the political logic of his commanders. Parental love has issued an order that military pragmatism will find impossible to honor.\n\nThe theological weight here is considerable. David in verse 5 is simultaneously the legitimate king whose authority is being defended by this army and the broken father whose most urgent concern is not his throne but his son's life. The same man who represents God's anointed king in the Davidic covenant (2 Sam. 7) is also the man whose sin has produced this son who is trying to kill him. The order to deal gently with Absalom is David's implicit acknowledgment that he cannot regard his own son as merely a military target — and that acknowledgment will cost him dearly."
