        "body": "Verses 6-8 compress the battle itself into three sentences. The people of Israel are defeated before David's servants (v. 7); twenty thousand fall in a single day (v. 7); and the forest — not the sword — is identified as the greater executioner (v. 8). The narrator's emphasis is deliberate. The forest of Ephraim is not passive terrain; it is an active agent. The word *akhal* (devoured) in verse 8 is the word for eating, consuming — the same word used of fire and plague. The forest eats people. This is the narrator's first signal that something more than military strategy is at work. Providence has arranged the terrain of this battle to accomplish what David's army could not accomplish by sword alone.\n\nThen verse 9 slows everything down. Absalom — described by name after the battle's general account, as if his fate is being held in reserve — is riding his royal mule when he meets David's servants. The mule passes under the thick branches of a great oak; Absalom's head 'caught fast' in the oak. The Hebrew *chazaq* (caught, took hold, was seized) is the word of being gripped, held fast, unable to break free. The mule — the animal of royal dignity — 'kept going' underneath him, carrying the trappings of kingship forward while the man claiming kingship hung suspended.\n\nThe narrator does not specify whether it is Absalom's hair that catches (though the reader of chapter 14 would assume so — his hair cut annually at two hundred shekels). What is specified is the result: hanging between heaven and earth. This phrase is not merely physical description. In the ancient worldview, heaven is the realm of the living God and earth is the realm of human life; to hang between them is to be excluded from both. Deuteronomy 21:23 pronounces that one hung on a tree is accursed of God. The narrator does not cite Deuteronomy, but any attentive reader of the Torah would feel its weight.\n\nThe scene with the unnamed soldier (vv. 10-13) is essential to the chapter's moral economy. He is not a coward — he is the only man in the chapter who takes the king's command seriously enough to refuse a bribe of ten pieces of silver and a warrior's belt (v. 11). His reasoning in verse 13 is exact: 'There is nothing hidden from the king' — the king would have known what happened, Joab would have denied ordering it, and the soldier would have paid with his life. The soldier's refusal honors the royal command in a way that Joab's pragmatism cannot. Joab's response — 'I will not waste time here with you' (v. 14) — is the dismissal of a man who has decided the king's command is an obstacle rather than an order.\n\nJoab drives three spears through Absalom's heart while he is still alive in the oak (v. 14), and then his ten armor-bearers finish the work (v. 15). The multiplication of killers — first Joab, then ten young men — may reflect either ritual completeness or simple military thoroughness. In either case, the execution is deliberate and thorough. What the forest began with Absalom's entrapment, Joab completes by force. The judgment is total.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yaar* (forest) appears four times in the chapter (vv. 6, 8, 17) — the narrator's insistence on the forest as an agent. *Akhal* in v. 8 is the word for consuming, devouring — used of fire, plague, and predators. *Talah* (hanging, v. 10) and the phrase *bayin hashamayim u-bayin ha'arets* ('between heaven and earth') carry the resonance of Deuteronomy 21:22-23's curse on the hanged man. *Na'ar* (young man) in David's command (v. 5) reappears in the soldier's refusal (v. 12) — the two men who honor the king's language are David and the unnamed soldier who refused to strike."
