        "body": "Verses 16-18 form a transitional unit between the battle's close and the messenger scene. Joab blows the trumpet, ending the pursuit — an act of mercy toward Israel's defeated soldiers that also demonstrates his unilateral control of the field (v. 16). Absalom is thrown into a pit in the forest and covered with a heap of stones (v. 17), then comes the narrator's only editorial comment in the chapter: 'all Israel fled, each to his tent.'\n\nThe burial under a heap of stones is not neutral in the Deuteronomistic narrative. It is the burial of the accursed. Achan, stoned for stealing devoted things, is buried under a heap of stones in the Valley of Achor (Joshua 7:26). The king of Ai is buried under a heap of stones at the city gate (Joshua 8:29). The same formula marks each: great transgression, execution, anonymous burial under stones. Absalom's burial associates him with these cursed figures. No named mourner tends his grave. The forest that executed him also buries him.\n\nVerse 18 is the narrator's most devastating artistic move. He pivots immediately from the shameful burial to Absalom's own monument — the pillar Absalom had erected in the King's Valley during his lifetime, because he had no son to preserve his memory. The irony is three-layered. First, Absalom feared being forgotten and so built a monument; he will be remembered only as a failed rebel. Second, his monument is in the King's Valley near Jerusalem — the seat of the kingdom he tried to steal; his burial is in an unnamed pit in a forest east of the Jordan. Third, the *yad* (hand/monument) he raised to assert his name against death stands in permanent contrast to the stone heap raised anonymously over his body. He trusted stone over son, self-assertion over God-given legacy. The result: the monument preserves a name of shame, and the pit receives a body without honor.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Matstsevet* (standing pillar) is the word for memorial stone or stele — also used of the pillars Jacob and Rachel erected (Gen. 31:45; 35:20). *Yad* literally means 'hand' — here used in the sense of 'memorial' or 'monument.' The combination *matstsevet* and *yad Avshalom* creates a double memorial vocabulary that underscores Absalom's obsessive self-commemoration. *Zakhar* (to remember, to preserve memory) in v. 18 is the root from which *zikaron* (memorial) derives — Absalom wanted a *zikaron* but erected only a *yad*."
