        "body": "The messenger sequence is one of the Old Testament's most psychologically sophisticated narrative units. It occupies nearly as much space as the battle itself — and deliberately so. The narrator's purpose is to replicate in the reader the same agonizing suspension that David experiences sitting between the two gates.\n\nAhimaaz the son of Zadok is a known quantity — a priest's son, a reliable runner, a man David will recognize and trust. He has already played this role once in the story (17:17-21, carrying intelligence for David during the flight from Jerusalem). His eagerness to run with 'good news' in verse 19 is genuine but theologically naive: he frames the victory as the LORD's deliverance without reckoning that the king's son's death makes it unreportable as 'good news.' Joab understands what Ahimaaz does not: the military victory and the death of Absalom cannot be disaggregated. He refuses Ahimaaz precisely because he knows David's emotional center of gravity and knows a man who cares about the king will be unable to deliver the full message (v. 20).\n\nThe Cushite is sent instead — a foreigner, loyal to Joab by service rather than by the deep personal ties that bind Ahimaaz to the house of Zadok and to David. He will say what needs to be said. But Ahimaaz cannot accept being left behind, and Joab finally relents (vv. 22-23). Ahimaaz takes the longer, flatter route through the plain and outruns the Cushite — arriving first, but with nothing complete to say.\n\nDavid's reading of the runners is a masterpiece of hope-under-dread. A single runner means good news (v. 25). A second runner confirms good news (v. 26). The watchman's identification of Ahimaaz triggers David's warmest hope: 'He is a good man and comes with good news' (v. 27). Ahimaaz arrives and delivers a message of military victory — real and true — and then, when David presses the only question that matters (v. 29), retreats into deliberate vagueness: 'I saw a great tumult but did not know what it was.' He who ran so urgently to bring news cannot bring the news that matters. The king is told to stand aside; he waits for the Cushite.\n\nThe structural shape of the scene is the theology of dread made narrative: what we most fear knowing is also what we most urgently need to know. David sitting between the two gates is David in the state of every man before devastating news arrives — hoping, reading signs, trusting good men, waiting. The narrator refuses to rush it."
